    </figure>

</introduction>


<subsection xml:id="subsec-charg_transf">
  <title>Methods of Transferring Charges:</title>
 <introduction>
  <p>
    Charge can neither be created nor be destroyed but  it can be transferred from one 
    object to another by the following processes. 
    <ol>
      <li>
        <term>Charging by Friction:</term> In this method two neutral objects are rubbed 
        together against each other to transfer charges from one object to another. 
        The object which gains electrons becomes negatively charged and the one which 
        looses electrons becomes positively charged. 
      </li>
      <li>
       <term> Charging by Conduction:</term> In this method charged object are brought in 
       contact to the other object to transfer charges. Uncharged object becomes charged 
       after touching by the charged object. When oppositely charged object brought in contact 
       with each other they lose their charges.	
      </li>
      <li>
       <term> Charging by Induction:</term> In this method an uncharged object is brought 
       near a charged object (no physical contact) to induce a positive and negative charge 
       on it. When charged object is in proximity of uncharged object it produces an 
       electrical force on electrons to move them from one part of object to another. 
       When an insulator is brought near a charged object electrons of insulator atoms 
       experience electrical force which stretches atoms to  displace center of gravity of
        positive charges and negative charges. This phenomenon of separation of charges is 
        called <em>polarization</em>. Hence in induction positive charges are separated 
        from negative charges to produce charges on an object.   
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
 </introduction>

 <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-electroscope">
  <title>Electrophorus:</title>

