  <p>
    It is a device used to produce charges using electrostatic induction. 
    It consists of an insulating base plate and a conducting disc (also known as electrophorus disc) 
    with an insulated handle [<xref ref="fig3"/>]. At first insulating plate is rubbed with silk, 
    fur, or wool which produces charges on the plate depending on the type of materials being 
    rubbed together. In the figure above negative charges are produced on the base plate. 
    Electrophorus disk is then brought in contact with this plate and then grounded. 
    Grounding help free charges on disk to neutralize with the opposite charges from the 
    earth (ground). Earth is an infinite source of charges and because electrons are lighter 
    than the positive charges electrons can easily come from earth to the disk to neutralize 
    free positive charges or they can leave the disc to the ground if they are free charges. 
    After grounding, the disk contains only one kind of charges, it is then disconnected from 
    ground before get removed from the plate. All the charges on the disk then spread around 
    its surface which can be stored and used as needed. In this case positive charges are stored from the disk. 
  </p>
 </subsubsection>

 <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-electrscp">
  <title>Electroscope:</title>
  <figure xml:id="electroscope">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="electroscope.png" width="40%"/>
</figure>
  <p>
    It is an instrument used to detect charge on a body.  It consists of two gold 
    (or silver or aluminum) leaves suspended from a conducting rod that leads to the 
    outside of an insulating glass container (<xref ref="electroscope"/>). 
    The rod has metallic ball attached at its top, when a charged object is 
    brought near the conducting ball or make in contact with it causes the leaves 
    to diverge because like charges repel each other. The nature of charge (positive 
    or negative) on any object can also be determined with the help of electroscope,
     by making its leaves charged with the known charges.
  </p>
 </subsubsection>
</subsection>
  

<subsection xml:id="subsec-coulmb_law">
  <title>Coulumb's Law</title>
 <introduction>
  <p>
    The force of attraction or repulsion between any two point charges is directly proportional 
    to the product of these charges and inversely proportional to the square of distance between them. 
    The direction of force is always acting along the line joining these two point charges. 
    If <m>F_{12}</m> is a force acting on charge <m> q_{1}</m> due to charge <m> q_{2},</m> 
    <m>F_{21}</m> is a force acting on charge <m> q_{2}</m> due to charge <m>q_{1},</m> 
    and <m> r_{12} </m> is a distance between the two charges (<xref ref="fig4"/>) then from Coulumb's law 
    <me>
      \vec{F}  =  k\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}}\hat{r} =  \frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_{o}}\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}}\hat{r}
    </me>
    where <m>\hat{r}</m> is unit vector along line joining the two charges, Coulomb's constant of free space, 
    <m>k  =  9.00 \times 10^{9} \,N m^{2}/C^{2}</m>;  and permittivity of free space, 
    <m>\epsilon_{o}  =  8.85 \times 10^{-12}\,C^{2}/N m^{2}.</m> 
    Permittivity is an ability of a medium to store electrical energy in an electric field. 
    In other words, permittivity is the extent to which a medium permits electrical lines of force 
    between the charges. It is a resistance of a medium in forming electric fields. It describes 
    the effect of a material in an electrical field. The higher the permittivity, the more the 
    material tends to reduce electrical field (due to polarization) that set up it. 
  </p>
