 <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-1d_colmb">
  <title>Coulumb's Law in One Dimension</title>
  <p>
    Coulomb's law holds good only for two point charges but if more than two charges are 
    located in space then the force on each of them can be determined by using the principle of superposition.
  </p>
 </subsubsection>

 <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-2d_colmb">
  <title>Coulomb's Law in Two and Three Dimensions</title>
  <p>
    Use principle of superposition to obtain force on any charge if the charges are distributed at different points in space. 
  </p>
 </subsubsection>
</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="subsec-superp_th">
  <title>Principle of Superposition</title>
  <p>
    It states that every charge in space exerts a force on another in such a way 
    that there are no other chrages present in that medium. Hence, the net force 
    excerted at a point charge by two or more charges in space is a vector sum 
    of the individual forces. 
  </p>
</subsection>
